{{Infobox venue | name = Athens Olympic Velodrome | nickname = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = [[File:Olympic stadium,Athens 25.JPG|260px]] | caption = Athens Olympic Velodrome | fullname = | former_names = | location = [[Marousi]], [[Athens]], [[Greece]] | coordinates = {{coord|38.0401|23.7804|type:landmark_region:GR|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1991 | renovated = 2004 | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = Afzelia hardwood | scoreboard = | estimated_cost = | suites = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = 5,250 | record_attendance = | executive_suites = | dimensions = {{convert|250|m|ft|abbr=on}} track | acreage = | tenants = }}
The '''Athens Olympic Velodrome''' is a [[Velodrome|velodrome stadium]] that is located in [[Marousi]], [[Athens]], [[Greece]], at the [[Athens Olympic Sports Complex]]. The stadium, which seats 5,250 - though only 3,300 seats were made publicly available for the [[2004 Summer Olympic Games]] - has distinctive twin roofs, covering the stands on each side.
==History== The Olympic Velodrome was originally built in 1991, for the [[1991 Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]]. It was extensively refurbished in order to host the [[Cycling at the 2004 Summer Olympics|track cycling]] events at the [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Athens Summer Olympics]]. It was redesigned for the 2004 Olympics by Spanish [[architect]] [[Santiago Calatrava]]. The track, made of [[Afzelia]] wood, is {{convert|250|m|ft}} long and {{convert|7.5|m|ft}} wide. Reconstruction of the stadium was completed on May 30, 2004, and it was officially re-opened on July 30, 2004.
