===Continental Cup Double Outside of Europe=== {{Empty section|date=April 2018}}
==Other== A combination of domestic league or cup and a lesser domestic or continental trophy may be won in the same season. Examples include (this list does not include doubles achieved as part of a treble):
* [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]'s 1960 team won both [[La Liga]] and the [[Fairs Cup]]. * [[Real Zaragoza]] won a [[Fairs Cup]] and [[Copa del Rey]] double in the 1963–64 season. * [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] were the first English team to win a double involving European and domestic trophies. It was in 1968 when Leeds won the [[1968 Football League Cup Final|Football League Cup]] and [[1967–68 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]].<ref name=Kry1>Chelsea also won the League Cup and the FA cup in 2007. [http://www.krysstal.com/league1968.html "Football : Season Details: 1968"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031105911/http://www.krysstal.com/league1968.html |date=31 October 2006 }} krysstal.com (accessed 17 October 2006)</ref> * [[Chicago Fire S.C.|Chicago Fire]] won the [[MLS Supporters' Shield]] and [[US Open Cup]] in 2003. * [[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Dinamo Tbilisi]] won the [[Georgian Cup]] and [[CIS Cup]] in 2004. * [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] won the [[Copa del Rey]] and [[Copa Catalunya]] in 2006. This would not normally be counted as a domestic cup double comparable to those mentioned above, as the latter competition is not nationwide or league-wide. * [[F.C. Copenhagen|FC Copenhagen]] won the [[Danish Superliga]] and the pan-Scandinavian [[Royal League]] in [[2005–06 F.C. Copenhagen season|2006]]. * [[FBK Kaunas]] won the [[Lithuanian Football Cup]] and [[Baltic League]] in 2008. * [[Al-Quwa Al-Jawiya]] won the [[Iraq FA Cup]] and [[AFC Cup]] in 2016. * [[Al-Quwa Al-Jawiya]] won the [[Iraqi Premier League]] and [[AFC Cup]] in 2017.
==International Double== A national team cannot usually win a [[FIFA World Cup]] and their continental championship in the same year because they are usually not held in the same year (except for the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] until 2010), but one which wins both titles consecutively could be said to have "done the double".
===World and continental champions=== *{{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] won the gold medal at the [[Football at the 1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1924 South American Championship]]. (Prior to the [[FIFA World Cup]]'s foundation in 1930, the Olympic champions were considered to be the world champions). *{{flagicon|West Germany}} [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] won [[UEFA Euro 1972]] and the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]] *{{flagicon|France}} [[France national football team|France]] won the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], the [[UEFA Euro 2000]] and the [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]] *{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] won the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] and the [[2004 Copa América]] *{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Spain national football team|Spain]] won [[UEFA Euro 2008]], the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2012]]
===World and other tournament champions=== *{{flagicon|Italy|1861}} [[Italy national football team|Italy]] won the [[1933–35 Central European International Cup]] and the [[1934 FIFA World Cup]] *{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] won the [[Panamerican Championship 1956|1956 Panamerican Championship]] and the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]] *{{flagicon|England}} [[England national football team|England]] won the [[1965–66 British Home Championship]] and the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]]
===Continental and other tournament champions=== *{{Flagicon|Iran|1964}} [[Iran national football team|Iran]] won the [[1970 RCD Cup]] and the [[1972 AFC Asian Cup]] *{{Flagicon|Ghana}} [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] won the [[1982 African Cup of Nations]], [[1982 West African Nations Cup]] and [[1983 West African Nations Cup]] *{{Flagicon|Ivory Coast}} [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]] won the [[CEDEAO Cup#1991 CEDEAO Cup|1991 CEDEAO Cup]] and the [[1992 African Cup of Nations]] *{{Flagicon|Argentina}} [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] won the [[1991 Copa América]], the [[1992 King Fahd Cup]] and the [[1993 Copa América]] *{{Flagicon|Saudi Arabia}} [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] won the [[1996 AFC Asian Cup]] and the [[1998 Arab Nations Cup]] *{{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] won the [[1997 Copa América]] and the [[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup]] *{{Flagicon|Mexico}} [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] won the [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] and the [[1999 FIFA Confederations Cup]] *{{Flagicon|Cameroon}} [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] won the [[2002 African Cup of Nations]] and the [[2003 CEMAC Cup]] *{{Flagicon|Iraq}} [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] won the [[Football at the 2005 West Asian Games|2005 West Asian Games]] and the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup]] *{{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] won the [[2007 Copa América]] and the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] *{{Flagicon|Japan}} [[Japan national football team|Japan]] won the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup]] and the [[2013 EAFF East Asian Cup]]
