==Double Winning Managers== {{Unreferenced section|date=May 2012}} * [[William Sudell]], as manager of [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] won the inaugural [[Football League Division One|First Division]] going unbeaten in the league (12 clubs:22 games) and won the eighteenth edition of the [[FA Cup]] without conceding a goal in that competition in 1888–89. * [[Jock Stein]] won the double on 9 occasions with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] between 1967 and 1977: 4 the doubles of the [[List of Scottish football champions|Scottish league championship]] and the [[Scottish Cup]], 3 the doubles of the [[List of Scottish football champions|Scottish league championship]] and the [[Scottish League Cup]] and 2 [[Treble (association football)|the Treble]]. * [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] has won the double on four occasions; with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in 1983–84, and with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 1993–94, 1995–96 and 1998–99. This achievement makes him the only manager to win the double on both sides of the [[Anglo-Scottish border]]. * [[Sven-Göran Eriksson]] is the only manager to win a domestic double in three different countries, having done so in Sweden, Portugal and Italy with [[IFK Göteborg]] (1981–82), [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] (1982–83) and [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] (1999–2000) respectively. Note that this included back-to-back double wins in separate countries. * [[Louis van Gaal]] won the double with [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in 1997–98 and [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in 2009–10; subsequent to his undefeated European Double with [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in 1994–95. * [[Massimiliano Allegri]], with [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], became the first manager in Italy to win the double four consecutive times, in 2014–15, 2015–16, 2016–17 and 2017–18.
==See also== *[[Treble (association football)|The Treble]] *[[Tuples in association football|The Quadruple]]
